{"title_page": "Camille Claudel 1915", "text_new": "{{short description|2013 film}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=April 2020}}\n{{Infobox film\n| name           = Camille Claudel 1915\n| image          = Camille Claudel 1915 poster.jpg\n| caption        = Film poster\n| director       = [[Bruno Dumont]]\n| producer       = [[Rachid Bouchareb]]<br>Jean Brehat <br> Muriel Merlin\n| writer         = Bruno Dumont\n| starring       = [[Juliette Binoche]]\n| music          = [[Johann Sebastian Bach]]\n| cinematography = Guillaume Deffontaines\n| editing        = Bruno Dumont <br> Basile Belkhiri\n| distributor    = [[Wild Bunch (film company)|Wild Bunch]]\n| released       = {{Film date|2013|2|12|Berlin|2013|3|13|France|df=yes}}\n| runtime        = 97 minutes\n| country        = France\n| language       = French\n}}\n\n'''''Camille Claudel 1915''''' is a 2013 French biographical film written and directed by [[Bruno Dumont]]. The film premiered in competition at the [[63rd Berlin International Film Festival]].<ref name=\"Berlin\">{{Cite web|url=http://www.berlinale.de/en/presse/pressemitteilungen/alle/Alle-Detail_16404.html |title=Berlinale Competition 2013: Another Nine Films Confirmed |accessdate=11 January 2013 |work=berlinale}}</ref>\n\n==Plot==\nAt the end of her career the sculptor [[Camille Claudel]] seems to suffer with mental issues. She destroys her own statues and utters repeatedly that her former lover [[Auguste Rodin]] intended to make her life miserable. Consequently, her younger brother [[Paul Claudel|Paul]] sends her to an [[History of psychiatric institutions|asylum]] on the outskirts of [[Avignon]]. Claudel tries to convince her doctor she is perfectly sane, while living among patients who obviously are not. She is desperate to see her brother again, hoping he might eventually support her plea.\n\n==Cast==\n* [[Juliette Binoche]] as Camille Claudel\n* Jean-Luc Vincent as Paul Claudel\n* Robert Leroy as the doctor\n* Emmanuel Kauffmann as the priest\n* Marion Keller as Miss Blanc\n* Armelle Leroy-Rolland as the young novice\n\n==Reception==\nAccording to ''[[Cine Vue]]''<nowiki>'</nowiki>s Patrick Gamble the filmmaker Bruno Dumont has delivered an \"incredibly compassionate and humble observation of a tortured artist\".<ref>{{cite web |title = Berlin Film Festival 2013: 'Camille Claudel 1915' review |url = http://www.cine-vue.com/2013/02/berlin-film-festival-2013-camille.html |work = Cine Vue |accessdate = 16 February 2013 |archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20130217223824/http://www.cine-vue.com/2013/02/berlin-film-festival-2013-camille.html# |archive-date = 17 February 2013 |url-status = dead }}</ref> ''[[Variety (magazine)|Variety]]''<nowiki>'</nowiki>s Guy Lodge described the film as a \"moving account of a brief period in the later life of the troubled sculptress\" and appreciated Juliette Binoche's impersonation of Camille Claudel as nothing less than \"mesmerising\".<ref>{{cite web |title =  'Camille Claudel 1915' review|url = https://www.variety.com/review/VE1117949237/|work = [[Variety (magazine)|Variety]] |accessdate = 12 February 2013}}</ref> ''[[Screen International]]''{{-'}}s Jonathan Romney ranked this film as \"an amplification and indeed a deepening\" of Dumont's hitherto existing accomplishments and artistic impact.<ref>{{cite web |title = Camille Claudel 1915 |url = http://www.screendaily.com/reviews/camille-claudel-1915/5051930.article |work = [[Screen International]] |accessdate = 12 February 2013}}</ref> Eric Kohn of [[IndieWire]] stated the film had a \"concision\" which displayed \"an exactitude worthy of [[Robert Bresson]]\".<ref>{{cite web |title = Berlin Review: Juliette Binoche Delivers Commanding Performance In Bruno Dumont's Powerful Crisis of Faith Drama 'Camille Claudel 1915' |url = https://www.indiewire.com/article/berlin-review-juliet-binoche-delivers-commanding-performance-in-bruno-dumons-powerful-crisis-of-faith-drama-camille-claudel-1915 |publisher = [[IndieWire]] |accessdate = 12 February 2013}}</ref> Analysing the film in depth for ''[[The Hollywood Reporter]]'', Jordan Mintzer summed up the film in his \"bottom line\": \"An unsettling portrait of the artist as a mad woman, anchored by a riveting lead performance\".<ref>{{cite web |title = Camille Claudel 1915: Berlin Review|url = https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/review/camille-claudel-1915-berlin-review-420879|work = [[The Hollywood Reporter]] |accessdate = 12 February 2013}}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n* [[Camille Claudel (film)|''Camille Claudel'']], 1988 film\n* ''[[Rodin (film)|Rodin]]'', 2017 film\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* [http://en.unifrance.org/movie/33564/camille-claudel-1915 ''Camille Claudel 1915''] at ''Uni France films''\n* {{IMDb title|2018086|Camille Claudel 1915}}\n\n{{Bruno Dumont|state=expanded}}\n{{Camille Claudel}}\n{{Auguste Rodin}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Camille Claudel 1915}}\n[[Category:2010s biographical drama films]]\n[[Category:2010s historical films]]\n[[Category:2013 films]]\n[[Category:Films directed by Bruno Dumont]]\n[[Category:French biographical drama films]]\n[[Category:French historical films]]\n[[Category:French films]]\n[[Category:French-language films]]\n[[Category:Biographical films about artists]]\n[[Category:Films set in psychiatric hospitals]]\n[[Category:Films set in 1915]]\n[[Category:Cultural depictions of Auguste Rodin]]\n[[Category:Cultural depictions of Camille Claudel]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|2013 film}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=December 2019}}\n{{Infobox film\n| name           = Camille Claudel 1915\n| image          = Camille Claudel 1915 poster.jpg\n| caption        = Film poster\n| director       = [[Bruno Dumont]]\n| producer       = [[Rachid Bouchareb]]<br>Jean Brehat <br> Muriel Merlin\n| writer         = Bruno Dumont\n| starring       = [[Juliette Binoche]]\n| music          = [[Johann Sebastian Bach]]\n| cinematography = Guillaume Deffontaines\n| editing        = Bruno Dumont <br> Basile Belkhiri\n| distributor    = [[Wild Bunch (film company)|Wild Bunch]]\n| released       = {{Film date|2013|2|12|Berlin|2013|3|13|France|df=yes}}\n| runtime        = 97 minutes\n| country        = France\n| language       = French\n}}\n\n'''''Camille Claudel 1915''''' is a 2013 French biographical film written and directed by [[Bruno Dumont]]. The film premiered in competition at the [[63rd Berlin International Film Festival]].<ref name=\"Berlin\">{{Cite web|url=http://www.berlinale.de/en/presse/pressemitteilungen/alle/Alle-Detail_16404.html |title=Berlinale Competition 2013: Another Nine Films Confirmed |accessdate=11 January 2013 |work=berlinale}}</ref>\n\n==Plot==\nAt the end of her career the sculptor [[Camille Claudel]] seems to suffer with mental issues. She destroys her own statues and utters repeatedly that her former lover [[Auguste Rodin]] intended to make her life miserable. Consequently, her younger brother [[Paul Claudel|Paul]] sends her to an [[History of psychiatric institutions|asylum]] on the outskirts of [[Avignon]]. Claudel tries to convince her doctor she is perfectly sane, while living among patients who obviously are not. She is desperate to see her brother again, hoping he might eventually support her plea.\n\n==Cast==\n* [[Juliette Binoche]] as Camille Claudel\n* Jean-Luc Vincent as Paul Claudel\n* Robert Leroy as the doctor\n* Emmanuel Kauffmann as the priest\n* Marion Keller as Miss Blanc\n* Armelle Leroy-Rolland as the young novice\n\n==Reception==\nAccording to ''[[Cine Vue]]''<nowiki>'</nowiki>s Patrick Gamble the filmmaker Bruno Dumont has delivered an \"incredibly compassionate and humble observation of a tortured artist\".<ref>{{cite web |title = Berlin Film Festival 2013: 'Camille Claudel 1915' review |url = http://www.cine-vue.com/2013/02/berlin-film-festival-2013-camille.html |work = Cine Vue |accessdate = 16 February 2013 |archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20130217223824/http://www.cine-vue.com/2013/02/berlin-film-festival-2013-camille.html# |archive-date = 17 February 2013 |url-status = dead }}</ref> ''[[Variety (magazine)|Variety]]''<nowiki>'</nowiki>s Guy Lodge described the film as a \"moving account of a brief period in the later life of the troubled sculptress\" and appreciated Juliette Binoche's impersonation of Camille Claudel as nothing less than \"mesmerising\".<ref>{{cite web |title =  'Camille Claudel 1915' review|url = https://www.variety.com/review/VE1117949237/|work = [[Variety (magazine)|Variety]] |accessdate = 12 February 2013}}</ref> ''[[Screen International]]''{{-'}}s Jonathan Romney ranked this film as \"an amplification and indeed a deepening\" of Dumont's hitherto existing accomplishments and artistic impact.<ref>{{cite web |title = Camille Claudel 1915 |url = http://www.screendaily.com/reviews/camille-claudel-1915/5051930.article |work = [[Screen International]] |accessdate = 12 February 2013}}</ref> Eric Kohn of [[IndieWire]] stated the film had a \"concision\" which displayed \"an exactitude worthy of [[Robert Bresson]]\".<ref>{{cite web |title = Berlin Review: Juliette Binoche Delivers Commanding Performance In Bruno Dumont's Powerful Crisis of Faith Drama 'Camille Claudel 1915' |url = https://www.indiewire.com/article/berlin-review-juliet-binoche-delivers-commanding-performance-in-bruno-dumons-powerful-crisis-of-faith-drama-camille-claudel-1915 |publisher = [[IndieWire]] |accessdate = 12 February 2013}}</ref> Analysing the film in depth for ''[[The Hollywood Reporter]]'', Jordan Mintzer summed up the film in his \"bottom line\": \"An unsettling portrait of the artist as a mad woman, anchored by a riveting lead performance\".<ref>{{cite web |title = Camille Claudel 1915: Berlin Review|url = https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/review/camille-claudel-1915-berlin-review-420879|work = [[The Hollywood Reporter]] |accessdate = 12 February 2013}}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n* [[Camille Claudel (film)|''Camille Claudel'']], 1988 film\n* ''[[Rodin (film)|Rodin]]'', 2017 film\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* [http://en.unifrance.org/movie/33564/camille-claudel-1915 ''Camille Claudel 1915''] at ''Uni France films''\n* {{IMDb title|2018086|Camille Claudel 1915}}\n\n{{Bruno Dumont|state=expanded}}\n{{Camille Claudel}}\n{{Auguste Rodin}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Camille Claudel 1915}}\n[[Category:2010s biographical drama films]]\n[[Category:2010s historical films]]\n[[Category:2013 films]]\n[[Category:Films directed by Bruno Dumont]]\n[[Category:French biographical drama films]]\n[[Category:French historical films]]\n[[Category:French films]]\n[[Category:French-language films]]\n[[Category:Biographical films about artists]]\n[[Category:Films set in psychiatric hospitals]]\n[[Category:Films set in 1915]]\n[[Category:Cultural depictions of Auguste Rodin]]\n[[Category:Cultural depictions of Camille Claudel]]\n", "name_user": "Lugnuts", "label": "safe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Camille_Claudel_1915"}
{"title_page": "Declaration on the Elimination of Discrimination Against Women", "text_new": "{{short description|Human rights proclamation issued by the United Nations General Assembly}}\n{{Violence against women}}\nThe '''Declaration on the Elimination of Discrimination against Women''' (abbreviated as '''DEDAW'''<ref>{{Cite book |last=Freeman |first=Marsha A. |display-authors=etal |date=2012 |title=The UN Convention on the Elimination of All Forms of Discrimination Against Women: A Commentary |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=HAENi8BnCrMC&pg=PA38 |location=Oxford |publisher=Oxford University Press |page=38 |isbn=9780199565061 |accessdate=14 March 2020}}</ref>) is a [[human rights]] proclamation issued by the [[United Nations General Assembly]], outlining that body's views on [[women's rights]].  It was adopted by the General Assembly on 7 November 1967.<ref>United Nations General Assembly Resolution 2263, 7 November 1967.</ref> The Declaration was an important precursor to the legally binding 1979 [[Convention on the Elimination of All Forms of Discrimination Against Women]] (CEDAW). It was drafted by the Commission on the Status of Women in 1967.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Evatt|first=Elizabeth|date=2002|title=Finding a voice for women's rights: The early days of CEDAW|url=|journal=George Washington International Law Review|volume=34|pages=515\u2013553|via=Proquest Central}}</ref>\n\n==Summary==\n\nThe Declaration follows the structure of the [[Universal Declaration of Human Rights]], with a preamble followed by eleven articles.\n\n'''Article 1''' declares that discrimination against women is \"fundamentally unjust and constitutes an offence against human dignity\".<ref>Declaration on the Elimination of Discrimination against Women, Article 1.</ref>  \"Discrimination\" is not defined.\n\n'''Article 2''' calls for the abolition of laws and customs which discriminate against women, for equality under the law to be recognised, and for states to ratify and implement existing UN human rights instruments against discrimination.\n\n'''Article 3''' calls for public education to eliminate [[prejudice]] against women.\n\n'''Article 4''' calls for women to enjoy full electoral rights, including the right to vote and the right to seek and hold public office.\n\n'''Article 5''' calls for women to have the same rights as men to change their [[nationality]].\n\n'''Article 6''' calls for women to enjoy full equality in [[Civil law (area)|civil law]], particularly around marriage and [[divorce]], and calls for child marriages to be outlawed.\n\n'''Article 7''' calls for the elimination of gender discrimination in criminal punishment.\n\n'''Article 8''' calls on states to combat all forms of traffic in women and exploitation of [[prostitution]] of women.\n\n'''Article 9''' affirms an equal [[right to education]] regardless of gender.\n\n'''Article 10''' calls for equal rights in the workplace, including non-discrimination in employment, [[equal pay for equal work]], and paid [[maternity leave]].\n\n'''Article 11''' calls on states to implement the principles of the Declaration.\n\n==See also==\n* [[Convention on the Elimination of All Forms of Discrimination Against Women]] (CEDAW)\n* [[United Nations Commission on the Status of Women]]\n* [[Women's rights]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* [http://www.lawphil.net/international/treaties/dec_nov_1967.html Declaration on the Elimination of Discrimination against Women]\n* [https://www.un.org/womenwatch/daw/cedaw/history.htm History of the CEDAW]\n\n{{International human rights legal instruments}}\n\n[[Category:Women's rights instruments]]\n[[Category:United Nations General Assembly resolutions]]\n[[Category:Proclamations]]\n[[Category:1967 in law]]\n[[Category:1967 in the United Nations]]\n[[Category:1967 in women's history]]\n[[Category:November 1967 events]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Human rights proclamation issued by the United Nations General Assembly}}\n{{Violence against women}}\nThe '''Declaration on the Elimination of Discrimination against Women''' (abbreviated as '''DEDAW'''<ref>{{Cite book |last=Freeman |first=Marsha A. |display-authors=etal |date=2012 |title=The UN Convention on the Elimination of All Forms of Discrimination Against Women: A Commentary |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=HAENi8BnCrMC&pg=PA38 |location=Oxford |publisher=Oxford University Press |page=38 |isbn=9780199565061 |accessdate=14 March 2020}}</ref>) is a [[human rights]] proclamation issued by the [[United Nations General Assembly]], outlining that body's views on [[women's rights]].  It was adopted by the General Assembly on 7 November 1967.<ref>United Nations General Assembly Resolution 2263, 7 November, 1967.</ref> The Declaration was an important precursor to the legally binding 1979 [[Convention on the Elimination of All Forms of Discrimination Against Women]] (CEDAW). It was drafted by the Commission on the Status of Women in 1967.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Evatt|first=Elizabeth|date=2002|title=Finding a voice for women's rights: The early days of CEDAW|url=|journal=George Washington International Law Review|volume=34|pages=515\u2013553|via=Proquest Central}}</ref> \n\n==Summary==\n\nThe Declaration follows the structure of the [[Universal Declaration of Human Rights]], with a preamble followed by eleven articles.\n\n'''Article 1''' declares that discrimination against women is \"fundamentally unjust and constitutes an offence against human dignity\".<ref>Declaration on the Elimination of Discrimination against Women, Article 1.</ref>  \"Discrimination\" is not defined.\n\n'''Article 2''' calls for the abolition of laws and customs which discriminate against women, for equality under the law to be recognised, and for states to ratify and implement existing UN human rights instruments against discrimination.\n\n'''Article 3''' calls for public education to eliminate [[prejudice]] against women.\n\n'''Article 4''' calls for women to enjoy full electoral rights, including the right to vote and the right to seek and hold public office.\n\n'''Article 5''' calls for women to have the same rights as men to change their [[nationality]].\n\n'''Article 6''' calls for women to enjoy full equality in [[Civil law (area)|civil law]], particularly around marriage and [[divorce]], and calls for child marriages tobe outlawed.\n\n'''Article 7''' calls for the elimination of gender discrimination in criminal punishment.\n\n'''Article 8''' calls on states to combat all forms of traffic in women and exploitation of [[prostitution]] of women.\n\n'''Article 9''' affirms an equal [[right to education]] regardless of gender.\n\n'''Article 10''' calls for equal rights in the workplace, including non-discrimination in employment, [[equal pay for equal work]], and paid [[maternity leave]].\n\n'''Article 11''' calls on states to implement the principles of the Declaration.\n\n==See also==\n* [[Convention on the Elimination of All Forms of Discrimination Against Women]] (CEDAW)\n* [[United Nations Commission on the Status of Women]]\n* [[Women's rights]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* [http://www.lawphil.net/international/treaties/dec_nov_1967.html Declaration on the Elimination of Discrimination against Women]\n* [https://www.un.org/womenwatch/daw/cedaw/history.htm History of the CEDAW]\n\n{{International human rights legal instruments}}\n\n\n[[Category:Women's rights instruments]]\n[[Category:United Nations General Assembly resolutions]]\n[[Category:Proclamations]]\n[[Category:1967 in law]]\n[[Category:1967 in the United Nations]]\n[[Category:1967 in women's history]]\n[[Category:November 1967 events]]\n", "name_user": "John of Reading", "label": "safe", "comment": "Typo/generalfixes, replaced: tobe \u2192 to be", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Declaration_on_the_Elimination_of_Discrimination_Against_Women"}
{"title_page": "Karthik Krishnan", "text_new": "{{Advert|date=April 2020}}\n'''Karthik Krishnan''' is an Indian-American Business executive and is the Global [[Chief executive officer|Chief Executive Officer]] (CEO) of [[Britannica]] Group. He is an [[Adjunct professor|Adjunct Professor]] at [[New York University Stern School of Business|Stern School of Business, New York University]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.stern.nyu.edu/faculty/bio/karthik-krishnan|title=NYU Stern - Karthik Krishnan - Adjunct Assistant Professor|last=Professor|first=-Adjunct Assistant|website=www.stern.nyu.edu|language=en|access-date=2020-04-08}}</ref> He is on the board of Britannica Knowledge Systems, which provides training management solutions to Airlines and Defense industries. \n[[File:Karthik_krishnan.jpg|thumb|Karthik Krishnan - Global CEO of Britannica Group<br />\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|+\n|Born\n|Karthik Krishnan (age 45)\n\nChennai, Tamil Nadu, India\n|-\n|Education\n|[[Coimbatore Institute of Technology]], [[Bharathiar University|Barathiar University]] (B.E)\n\n[[Stern school of business|Stern School of Business]], New York (MBA)\n|-\n|Title\n|Global CEO of [[Encyclop\u00e6dia Britannica|Britannica]] groups\n|-\n|Board member of\n|Britannica Knowledge Systems\n|-\n|Spouse\n|Deepa Krishnan\n|-\n|Children\n|2\n|}\n]]\nKarthik Krishnan was born in [[Chennai|Chennai, Tamil Nadu]]. He graduated from [[Bharathiar University]], with a Bachelor's degree in [[Engineering]] and a Master's degree in [[Business administration|Business Administration]] from Stern School of Business under New York University. He was appointed the Global CEO of Britannica Group in the Fall of 2017.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.stern.nyu.edu/faculty/bio/karthik-krishnan|title=NYU Stern - Karthik Krishnan - Adjunct Assistant Professor|last=Professor|first=-Adjunct Assistant|website=www.stern.nyu.edu|language=en|access-date=2020-04-08}}</ref><ref>{{Cite journal|last=Makar|first=A. B.|last2=McMartin|first2=K. E.|last3=Palese|first3=M.|last4=Tephly|first4=T. R.|date=June 1975|title=Formate assay in body fluids: application in methanol poisoning|url=https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/1|journal=Biochemical Medicine|volume=13|issue=2|pages=117\u2013126|doi=10.1016/0006-2944(75)90147-7|issn=0006-2944|pmid=1}}</ref> \u00a0\n\n== Early Life and Education ==\nKarthik was born and raised in [[Chennai|Chennai, Tamil Nadu]]. He did his schooling in G.K Shetty Vivekananda Vidyalaya, Ambattur and T I Matriculation Higher Secondary School, Ambattur. Post which, he went to [[Coimbatore Institute of Technology]] and graduated in 1995 with a Bachelor's degree in Engineering. In 2006, he received his Master's degree in Business Administration from [[New York University Stern School of Business|Stern School of Business, New York]]. \u00a0In 2015, he also earned a certificate in [[Design thinking|Design Thinking]] from [[Stanford University]]. He is certified in board governance and is a [[National Association of Corporate Directors]] (NACD) Governance Fellow since 2013.\n\n== Career ==\nHe started his career as a [[software engineer]] working on the then-emerging [[Rich web application|Internet applications]] and then moved on to work as a [[digital strategy]] and transformation consultant for [[Rodale, Inc.|Rodale Inc]]. The publisher of healthy active living magazines including [[Men's Health|Men\u2019s Health]], [[Backpacker (magazine)|Backpacker]], [[Runner's World|Runner\u2019s World]], Prevention; and books including Al Gore\u2019s Inconvenient Truth and South Beach Diet.\n\nIn 2006, Karthik joined [[RELX]] (formerly [[Reed Elsevier]]) as [[Vice president|Vice President]] Interactive Media and Sales Management for 44 brands including [[Variety (magazine)|Variety]], [[Broadcasting & Cable]], [[Multichannel News]], Interior Design and Hotels . He then went on to lead the Global Pharma Business and [[e-commerce]] channel at [[Elsevier, Inc.|Elsevier Inc]] as Senior [[Vice president|Vice President]] & [[General manager|General Manager]]. He then took on the Global Clinical Reference & Workflow business at [[Elsevier|Elsevier Inc]] and launched products that won industry recognition including Best in KLAS and [[Frost & Sullivan]] Technology Innovation awards.\n\nHe joined [[Encyclop\u00e6dia Britannica|Britannica]] in November 2017.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.connectedtoindia.com/indian-american-karthik-krishnan-appointed-ceo-of-encyclopedia-britannica-group-3362.html|title=Indian-American Karthik Krishnan appointed CEO of Encyclopedia Britannica Group|website=www.connectedtoindia.com|access-date=2020-04-08}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.cio.com/article/3525005/encyclopedia-britannica-ceo-karthik-krishnan-explains-how-he-works-with-his-cto-and-cpo.html|title=Encyclopedia Britannica CEO explains how he works with his CTO and CPO|last=Trueman|first=Charlotte|date=2019-04-29|website=CIO|language=en|access-date=2020-04-08}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.indiawest.com/news/global_indian/indian-american-karthik-krishnan-named-global-ceo-of-encyclopaedia-britannica-group/article_8af7a4e4-e782-11e7-a1b2-131f9b162cf7.html|title=Indian American Karthik Krishnan Named Global CEO of Encyclopaedia Britannica Group|last=Reporter|first=India-West Staff|website=India West|language=en|access-date=2020-04-08}}</ref> He launched a pair of ideas having these two themes as moto:\n\n1. Elevate better information in the digital universe\n\n2. Transform learning inside and outside the classroom<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.asiaoutlookmag.com/industry-insights/article/725-exclusive-interview-encyclopdia-britannica-ceo-karthik-krishnan|title=Asia Outlook Magazine|website=www.asiaoutlookmag.com|access-date=2020-04-08}}</ref>\n\nKarthik Krishnan firstly introduced Britannica Insights, a [[Google Chrome]] browser extension<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://securityboulevard.com/2020/02/concentric-applies-deep-learning-algorithms-to-data-security/|title=Concentric Applies Deep Learning Algorithms to Data Security|last=February 3|first=Michael Vizard on|last2=2020|date=2020-02-03|website=Security Boulevard|language=en-US|access-date=2020-04-08}}</ref> that allows users who are searching to cut through the clutter, buy time, study more and ensure that the results are almost as same as the results that show up on search engines like [[Google]], [[Yahoo!|Yahoo]], and [[Bing (search engine)|Bing]]. Then came the next product observed by the concept of Britannica School Insights,<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://wgnradio.com/the-download/the-download-on-chicago-business/how-does-britannica-remain-relevant-after-250-years-in-business/|title=How does Britannica remain relevant after 250 years in business?|date=2018-10-05|website=WGN Radio 720 - Chicago's Very Own|language=en-US|access-date=2020-04-08}}</ref> which supplied comparable content for subscribers of Britannica\u2019s online classroom solutions and a partnership with [[YouTube]] on various conspiracy theories at the platform.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://profiles.forbes.com/members/business/profile/Karthik-Krishnan-Global-CEO-Britannica-Group-Britannica-Merriam-Webster-Britannica-Knowledge-System-and-Melingo/c54fec98-e22b-431c-820d-8743bb0f454b|title=Karthik Krishnan, Official Member of Forbes Councils|website=Forbes Councils|access-date=2020-04-08}}</ref> \u00a0\n\nBritannica LumieLabs was launched in early 2019 and won the teachers desire award for Classroom. LumieLabs help students become Digital Storytellers. The groundbreaking and smooth to apply video-production Platform promotes 21st century abilities along with [[Media literacy|Media Literacy]], [[Curiosity]], [[Creativity]] and [[Collaboration]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.prweb.com/releases/argentinas_education_ministry_and_encyclopaedia_britannica_partner_to_enable_remote_learning/prweb17022182.htm|title=Argentina\u2019s Education Ministry and Encyclopaedia Britannica Partner to Enable Remote Learning|website=PRWeb|access-date=2020-04-08}}</ref>\n\nKarthik has been listed among the Top 100 global influencer in [[EdTech]] by EdTech Digest.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Wiesmann|first=U. N.|last2=DiDonato|first2=S.|last3=Herschkowitz|first3=N. N.|date=1975-10-27|title=Effect of chloroquine on cultured fibroblasts: release of lysosomal hydrolases and inhibition of their uptake|url=https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/4|journal=Biochemical and Biophysical Research Communications|volume=66|issue=4|pages=1338\u20131343|doi=10.1016/0006-291x(75)90506-9|issn=1090-2104|pmid=4}}</ref> Guardians of History launched in the Fall of 2019 which is a voice and [[Artificial intelligence|AI]]-driven choose-your-own-adventure for kids. This resulted in Britannica being recognized as a Top 20 brand in voice innovation.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.globenewswire.com/news-release/2019/12/09/1958083/0/en/Samsung-collaborates-with-Britannica-and-Merriam-Webster-to-bring-On-This-Day-and-Word-of-the-Day-to-Samsung-s-Family-Hub-Smart-Refrigerators.html|title=Samsung collaborates with Britannica and Merriam-Webster to bring On This Day and Word of the Day to Samsung\u2019s Family Hub Smart Refrigerators|last=Inc|first=Merriam-Webster|date=2019-12-09|website=GlobeNewswire News Room|access-date=2020-04-08}}</ref> \u00a0 \u00a0\n\nKarthik has also authored published articles on various technology and education based topics.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Smith|first=R. J.|last2=Bryant|first2=R. G.|date=1975-10-27|title=Metal substitutions incarbonic anhydrase: a halide ion probe study|url=https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/3|journal=Biochemical and Biophysical Research Communications|volume=66|issue=4|pages=1281\u20131286|doi=10.1016/0006-291x(75)90498-2|issn=0006-291X|pmid=3}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.fenews.co.uk/press-releases/40906-addressing-the-curriculum-needs-and-challenges-of-new-ofsted-inspection-framework|title=Addressing the curriculum needs and challenges of new Ofsted Inspection framework|last=Learning|first=Britannica Digital|website=FE News|language=en-gb|access-date=2020-04-08}}</ref>\n\n== Personal life ==\nKarthik is married to Deepa Krishnan and has two children. They reside in [[Short Hills, New Jersey]]. His father, Late Prof. K Seshadrinathan was a Physics Professor and Head of Department at [[Murugappa Polytechnic College|Murugappa Polytechnic]] who later moved on to become a Business School Professor at [[University of Madras|Madras University]]. His mother, Sitalakshmi Seshadrinathan was a Maths teacher and is the founder of Gymnasium for brain.\n\n== Articles Published ==\n'''[[World Economic Forum]]''' <ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.weforum.org/agenda/2020/04/our-education-system-is-losing-relevance-heres-how-to-update-it/|title=Our education system is losing relevance. Here's how to update it|website=World Economic Forum|language=en|access-date=2020-04-20}}</ref>: 3 vital skills for the age of disruption\n\n'''[[Forbes]]''': Spot top talent with LID: Learning agility, Initiative and Drive\n\n'''CIO''': Keeping learning at the heart of Britannica's digital evolution\n\n== External links ==\n<nowiki>https://www.britannica-ks.com/board-of-directors/</nowiki>\n\n== References ==\n__FORCETOC__\n\n<references />\n\n\n17. [https://www.weforum.org/agenda/2019/09/3-vital-skills-for-the-age-of-disruption/ 3 Vital Skills for the age of disruption]\n[[Category:New York University Stern School of Business alumni]]\n", "text_old": "{{Advert|date=April 2020}}\n'''Karthik Krishnan''' is an Indian-American Business executive and is the Global [[Chief executive officer|Chief Executive Officer]] (CEO) of [[Britannica]] Group. He is an [[Adjunct professor|Adjunct Professor]] at [[New York University Stern School of Business|Stern School of Business, New York University]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.stern.nyu.edu/faculty/bio/karthik-krishnan|title=NYU Stern - Karthik Krishnan - Adjunct Assistant Professor|last=Professor|first=-Adjunct Assistant|website=